[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(34) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Anoint him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " . . . king.—It is notable that of this solemn inauguration of royalty, marked emphatically as a religious consecration by the common phrase “the Lord’s anointed”—then especially in use (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 16:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 24:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 26:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 1:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 19:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), though found also occasionally in the later books (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Lamentations 4:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ")—there is no mention of the tumultuous usurpation of Adonijah. Probably, as in the appointment of Saul and David himself, the right to anoint was recognised as belonging to the prophetic order (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 19:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), inasmuch as it signified the outpouring of the Holy Spirit of the Lord. (Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 10:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) Hence, in the absence of Nathan, it could not be attempted. In the case of David, such anointing had marked (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 16:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") his first private designation for the kingdom by Samuel, and his public accession to royalty, first over Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 2:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), then over all Israel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 5:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The completeness of the old King’s provision is especially to be noticed. The “riding on the King’s mule,” attended by the body-guard, marked the royal sanction; the anointing, the sanction of priest and prophet; and the acclamation the adhesion of the people. Then are to follow the enthronement and homage.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:34",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 1:34",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Let Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet anoint him — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is, say the Jews, one of them poured out the oil, and the other anointed his head, drawing a circle round about it with oil, according to their maxim that their kings were anointed in the form of a crown, to denote their delegation to the royal dignity. It is of more importance to observe, that this unction signified not only the designation of the person anointed to his office, but the gifts and graces which were necessary to qualify him for it, and which, seeking them sincerely of God, he might expect to receive. “We do not find,” says Henry, “that Abiathar pretended to anoint Adonijah: he was made king by a feast, not by unction. Whom God calls, he will qualify, which was signified by the anointing: usurpers had it not. Christ signifies ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "anointed, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and he is the king whom God hath ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "set upon his holy hill of Zion, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "according to the decree, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 2:6-7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Christians, also, are ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "made to our God, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and by him, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "kings, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and they have ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "an unction from the Holy One, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 John 2:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "1:32-53 The people expressed great joy and satisfaction in the elevation of Solomon. Every true Israelite rejoices in the exaltation of the Son of David. Combinations formed upon evil principles will soon be dissolved, when self-interest calls another way. How can those who do evil deeds expect to have good tidings? Adonijah had despised Solomon, but soon dreaded him. We see here, as in a glass, Jesus, the Son of David and the Son of God, exalted to the throne of glory, notwithstanding all his enemies. His kingdom is far greater than that of his father David, and therein all the true people of God cordially rejoice. The prosperity of his cause is vexation and terror to his enemies. No horns of the altar, nor forms of godliness, nor pretences to religion, can profit those who will not submit to His authority, and accept of his salvation; and if their submission be hypocritical, they shall perish without remedy.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Anoint him - Inauguration into each of the three offices (those of prophet, priest, and king) typical of the Messiah or Anointed One, was by anointing with oil. Divine appointment had already instituted the rite in connection with the kingly office ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 2:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; but after Solomon we have no express mention of the anointing of kings, except in the three cases of Jehu, Joash, and Jehoahaz ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 9:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", who were all appointed irregularly. At the time of the captivity, kings, whose anointing has not been related in the historical books, still bear the title of \"the anointed of the Lord.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Lamentations 4:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 89:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 89:51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "34. anoint him—done only in the case of a new dynasty or disputed succession (see on [286]1Sa 16:13; [287]2Sa 2:1).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
