  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And let Zadok the priest, and Nathan the prophet, anoint him there king over Israel,.... For it might be done by either of them, as the unctions of Saul and David show: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and blow ye the trumpet, and say, God save King Solomon; the blowing of the trumpet was to make it public; the proclamation of him as king was to be made by the sound of it, and the acclamation of the people was to express their concurrence with it, their loyal affection to the new king, and their hearty wishes for his health, prosperity, and long life. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and blow ye the trumpet, and say, God save King Solomon; the blowing of the trumpet was to make it public; the proclamation of him as king was to be made by the sound of it, and the acclamation of the people was to express their concurrence with it, their loyal affection to the new king, and their hearty wishes for his health, prosperity, and long life. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Geneva Study Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cverse2",
        "text": "And let Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet anoint him there king over Israel: and blow ye with the trumpet, and say, God save king Solomon.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "anoint him there",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The anointing was the most solemn portion of the ceremonies connected with the installation of a new king. We only read of its being done on some very marked occasions. Thus Saul, the first king, was anointed (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 10:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and David, the king of God’s own choice (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 16:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); also when God orders the prophet Elijah to make provision for a new succession in Israel, Jehu is to be anointed (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 19:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which was done when the proper time came (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 9:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 9:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); so Joash after his preservation was anointed by Jehoiada (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 23:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But though unmentioned it may have been performed in other cases. For ‘anointing’ is mentioned even in Jotham’s parable (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 9:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), where the trees will choose them a king. The ceremony is intended to symbolize the outpouring of gifts from above upon the new monarch.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "blow ye with the trumpet",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Thus did Jehu’s companions after his anointing (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 9:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); neither anointing nor the blowing of the trumpets has been mentioned in connexion with Adonijah’s faction. No doubt they wished to gain strength before making such a public display of what they were doing.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 34.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And let Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Bahr sees in the fact that Nathan was associated with Zadok in the anointing, \"the high significance David attributed to the prophetic office in Israel\" But the prophets constantly performed this ceremony. Samuel anointed both Saul and David; Elisha anointed Jehu (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 9:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and was commissioned to anoint Hazael (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 19:15, 16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ] anoint him [the king, being a sacred personage, was set apart to the office, like the priest and prophet, by anointing. Saul was probably anointed twice (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 10:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 11:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Cf. 12:3). David was anointed thrice (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 16:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 2:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 5:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Solomon was anointed twice (ver. 39; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 29:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
